__pycache__/
*.pyc
.DS_Store

# Real subscriber PII (email addresses) and dry-run send logs (which contain
# the same PII, since dry-run logs exactly what WOULD have been sent). Never
# commit either -- only subscribers.example.json (fake data) is tracked.
#
# Abuse-hardening audit (2026-07-03) widened this from an enumerated list of
# exact filenames/prefixes to a CONTENT-SHAPE denylist: ignore every
# JSON/JSONL file under reminders/ (the shape every PII-bearing or generated-
# state file in this package takes) except the one deliberately-fake example,
# rather than trying to keep enumerating every scratch-file naming
# convention a future test/attack script might invent. Found by the audit's
# own attack test: the old enumerated rules (exact paths + a `_test_*`
# prefix rule) missed a sibling agent's `_attack_row6_script.py` and a
# same-shaped `_attack_*.json` scratch file sitting untracked in the working
# tree during this very audit -- a live, reproduced instance of exactly the
# gap being described, not a hypothetical.
reminders/*.json
!reminders/subscribers.example.json
reminders/*.jsonl
reminders/*.log
reminders/*.env
reminders/.env
# Atomic-write temp files (sender.py's CircuitBreakerSender writes to a
# .tmp file then os.replace()s it into place -- a crash mid-write could
# leave one of these behind).
reminders/*.tmp

# Any scratch file (test harness OR ad-hoc attack/debug script, whatever
# extension) using the leading-underscore convention this codebase already
# uses for throwaway files -- catches `_test_*`, `_attack_*`, and any future
# prefix automatically instead of enumerating each one as it's invented.
# `__init__.py` is a REAL tracked source file that happens to start with an
# underscore -- explicitly un-ignored below so this rule can't silently drop
# it from the repo.
reminders/_*
!reminders/__init__.py
